# FRONTEND DEVELOPMENT RULES

## UI/UX Patterns

### Loading States
- Always show loading indicators for async operations
- Use appropriate loaders: spinner or progress bar
- Show button loading states during mutations

### Error Handling
- Display user-friendly error messages
- Show errors inline for form validation
- Use toast for global errors
- Provide actionable error messages when possible
- Log errors to console for debugging

### Empty States
- Show meaningful empty states for lists and data views
- Provide clear next actions (e.g., "Create your first item")

## Styling & Theming

### Theme Consistency
- Use theme variables from your theme configuration
- Avoid hardcoded colors - use semantic tokens instead


### Responsive Design
- Build mobile-first, then enhance for larger screens
- Test layouts on multiple screen sizes
- Use responsive utilities from your UI framework
- Ensure touch targets are appropriately sized on mobile

## Forms & Validation
- Validate user input on the client side for immediate feedback
- Show validation errors inline near the relevant field
- Disable submit button while form is submitting
- Clear errors when user corrects input
- Use proper input types (email, number, etc.)

## Data Fetching
- Use RTK Query for API calls and caching
- Handle loading, error, and success states
- Implement proper error retry logic
- Cache data appropriately to reduce unnecessary requests
- Show stale data while refetching when appropriate

## Performance

### Optimization
- Lazy load routes and heavy components
- Debounce search inputs and frequent API calls
- Memoize expensive computations with useMemo
- Use React.memo for components that render frequently with same props
- Only optimize when you identify an actual performance issue

### Bundle Size
- Code-split routes using dynamic imports
- Avoid importing entire libraries when you only need parts
- Keep dependencies lean - audit before adding new packages


## TypeScript
- Define clear types for props and state
- Use interfaces for object shapes
- Avoid `any` type - use `unknown` if type is truly unknown
- Define API types in `apiTypes.ts`
- Use proper type guards for runtime checks

## Code Organization
- Keep components focused and single-purpose
- Extract complex logic into custom hooks
- Keep files under 300 lines when practical (can be avoided or tweaked in exceptional cases)
- Group related functionality together

## Best Practices
- Remove unused imports and dead code
- Follow consistent code formatting
- Keep dependency arrays in hooks accurate
- Clean up side effects in useEffect
- Avoid nested ternaries - use early returns instead
- Write self-documenting code with clear names